e the Soviet collapse in 1991, the Church has worked its way into the nuclear forces, the most significant wing of one of the world's most powerful military organizations. Dmitry Adamsky describes how the Orthodox faith has merged with Russian national identity as the Church continues to expand its influence on foreign and domestic politics. The Church both legitimizes and influences Moscow's assertive national security strategy in the twenty-first century. This book sheds light on the role of faith in modern militaries and highlights the implications of this phenomenon for international security. Ultimately, Russian Nuclear Orthodoxy interrogates the implications of the confluence of religion and security for other members of the nuclear club, beyond Russia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aChurch and statexRusskai︠a︡ pravoslavnai︠a︡ t︠s︡erkovʹ. 0aChurch and statezRussia (Federation) 0aChurch and statezRussia (Federation). 0aNuclear warfarexReligious aspectsxRusskai︠a︡ pravoslavnai︠a︡ t︠s︡erkovʹ. 0aNuclear weaponsxGovernment policyzRussia (Federation) 0aNuclear weaponsxGovernment policyzRussia (Federation). 0aNuclear weaponszRussia (Federation) 0aNuclear weaponszRussia (Federation). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aPresident Putin.  aRussian Orthodox Church.  achurch-military relations.  anational ideology.  anational security policy.  anuclear strategy.  anuclear weapons.  apolitical myths.  astate-church relations.  athe Patriarch.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z9783110704594oZ